               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000063-1">
                      According to inscriptions on the eave column in front of the hall, Mahavira Hall was rebuilt in the fifth year of Shaosheng reign period (1098), and had major renovations in the fifth to twelfth years of Wanli reign period (1577-1584), the ninth to tenth years of Shunzhi reign period (1652-1653), and the third year of Tongzhi reign period (1864). The base of the hall is made of bricks. The main hall is a three-by-three <term ref="/keyword/k000149">bay</term> hall. Although its size is relatively small compared to other buildings, it is still within the range for image halls of smaller monasteries in this area (Miller 2011, 182). The main hall has a square plan and a single-eaves <term ref="/keyword/k000143">hip-gable roof (xieshanding 歇山頂)</term>. The roofridge-figures are made of yellow and green glaze, and their shapes and technique are all in Ming-style (Guojia wenwuju 2006, 305). Inside of the main hall, the transverse structure (liangjia 梁架)  is six rafters deep with a four-<term ref="/keyword/k000107">rafter</term> beam (sichuanfu 四椽栿) abutting a <term ref="/keyword/k000140">rufu (乳栿)</term> supported by three columns. On top of the three columns, there are 5-<term ref="/keyword/k000013">puzuo (铺作)</term> <term ref="/keyword/k000019">bracket sets (dougong 斗拱)</term> with single <term ref="/keyword/k000178">slanted arm (xia‘ang 下昂)</term> and single <term ref="/keyword/k000172">perpendicular bracket arm (huagong 華栱)</term>. There are also  bracket sets carved in relief (yinke dougong 隐刻斗拱) between the columns. Four panels of six-gridlattice partition doors (六抹格扇門) are hung on the central bay of both front and back facades , and two secondary bays both hold windows. Inside the back wall and gable-end walls are decorated with 34.10 square meters of meticulous and deeply colored Buddhist narrative murals. Based on the stele inscription and the art style of the frescos, the mural on the west side should have been painted in the Wanli reign period (1573-1620), and the mural on the east gable might be painted during the renovation in the tenth years of Shunzhi reign (1653) (Song Wenqiang 2010, 55).  
                  </p>
